Question 1.a

## Objective: To check if the customers who are returning rating the questions higher than who are not
## Type of Data: Ordinal
## Types of Sample: Independent
## Definition: People who are returning as sample 1 and who are not as sample 2

Hypothesis:

\(H_{o}\) : The two population locations are the same

\(H_{1}\) : The location of population 1 is to the right of the location of population 2

df_automobile$Return<-factor(df_automobile$Return,levels=c(2,1))
wilcox.test(as.integer(df_automobile$Quality) ~ as.factor(df_automobile$Return),alt='greater',paired = FALSE, exact = FALSE, conf.level=0.95)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  as.integer(df_automobile$Quality) by as.factor(df_automobile$Return)
## W = 2283.5, p-value = 2.327e-08
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is greater than 0
## Interpretation: The data provides sufficient evidence to infer that the customers who are returning rating the quality question higher than who are not
## The Objective and other steps would be almost similar to the ones mentioned above for the remaining questions

Question 1.b

## Objective: To check if the customers rating of the questions differ based on their comment sentiment
## Type of Data: Ordinal
## Types of Sample: Independent
## Definition: Denote Positive Comment - Population 1, No comment - Population 2, Negative Comment - Population 3

Hypothesis:

\(H_{o}\) : The locations of all three populations are the same.

\(H_{1}\) : At least two population locations differ.

df_automobile$Comment<-factor(df_automobile$Comment,levels=c(1,3,2))
kruskal.test(as.integer(df_automobile$Quality) ~ as.factor(df_automobile$Comment))
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  as.integer(df_automobile$Quality) by as.factor(df_automobile$Comment)
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 8.0915, df = 2, p-value = 0.0175
## The P-value is less than 0.05 significance level, so we decide to reject the null hypothesis and infer that the ratings differe for atleast two of the comment categories
kruskal.test(as.integer(df_automobile$Fairness) ~ as.factor(df_automobile$Comment))

df_drink <- read.csv("Soft Drink Recipe.csv")
head(df_drink,2)
##   Person Original New.Recipe.1 New.Recipe..2
## 1      1        5            5             5
## 2      2        3            4             5
## Objective: To check if the people rating the three drinks differently
## Type of Data: Ordinal
## Types of Sample: Blocked Design
## Definition:Denote Original Population 1, New Recipe 1- Population-2, New Recipe 2- Population-3

Hypothesis:

\(H_{o}\) : The locations of all three populations are the same.

\(H_{1}\) : At least two population locations differ.

df_drink_stack <- melt(df_drink, id.vars="Person")
names(df_drink_stack) <- c("Person","Recipe","Rating")
df_drink_stack$Recipe <- factor(df_drink_stack$Recipe, level = c("Original","New.Recipe.1","New.Recipe..2"))
friedman.test(df_drink_stack$Rating, as.factor(df_drink_stack$Recipe),as.factor(df_drink_stack$Person))
## 
##  Friedman rank sum test
## 
## data:  df_drink_stack$Rating, as.factor(df_drink_stack$Recipe) and as.factor(df_drink_stack$Person)
## Friedman chi-squared = 7.1525, df = 2, p-value = 0.02798
## Interpretation: As p-value less than 0.05, we can reject the null hypothesis and say that there is significant difference between atleast two recipes
library(PMCMRplus)
PMCMRplus::frdAllPairsNemenyiTest(df_drink_stack$Rating, as.factor(df_drink_stack$Recipe),as.factor(df_drink_stack$Person))
## 
##  Pairwise comparisons using Nemenyi-Wilcoxon-Wilcox all-pairs test for a two-way balanced complete block design
## data: y, groups and blocks
##               Original New.Recipe.1
## New.Recipe.1  0.559    -           
## New.Recipe..2 0.057    0.415
## 
## P value adjustment method: single-step

## Type of Data: Interval
## Types of Sample: Blocked Design
## Definition:Machine 1 -Population 1, Machine 2 - Population 2

Hypothesis:

\(H_{o}\) : The two population locations are the same

\(H_{1}\) : The two populations are different

wilcox.test(df_time_stack$Time~df_time_stack$Machine,alt="two.sided",paired=TRUE,exact=FALSE,conf.level = 0.95)
## 
##  Wilcoxon signed rank test with continuity correction
##

## Type of Data: Interval
## Types of Sample: Independent samples

\(H_{o}\) : \(\mu{1}\) \(=\) \(\mu{2}\)

\(H_{1}\) : \(\mu{1}\) \(\neq\) \(\mu{2}\)

t.test(df_cred$Applied,df_cred$Contacted,

##  130.9252  126.1356

8.a

## Some of cofounding variables would be:
## 1. People on the different geographies might have different preferences.
## 2. Environment, work culture, and health costs variation between the two extreme coasts might influence the employee preferences.
## These might cause influence their decision in turn applying the same policy to entire company might not be right decision

8.b

## Objective: To determine if the health benefits causing higher retention
## Level of Measurement: Nominal
## Experiment: Independent
## Definition:

Hypothesis:

\(H_{o}\) : \(P_{1}\) \(-\) \(P_{2}\) = 0.05

\(H_{1}\) : \(P_{1}\) \(-\) \(P_{2}\) > 0.05

df_ben %>% group_by(Benefit) %>% summarise(count = n(),
                                                 retained = sum(Retention))
## # A tibble: 2 × 3
##   Benefit  count retained
##   <chr>    <int>    <int>
## 1 Health     125      107
## 2 Vacation   140      109
p1 <- 107/125
p2 <- 109/140
n1 <- 125
n2 <- 140
C <- 0.05
SE = sqrt((p1*(1-p1)/n1 + p2*(1-p2)/n2))
z = ((p1 - p2) - C)/SE
1 - pnorm(abs(z))
## [1] 0.2801272
## As the p-value greater than any significance vlaue, we won't be reject the null hypothesis and we can't say that health benefits is better in providing the better employee retention

8.c

Hypothesis:

\(H_{o}\) : \(P_{1}\) \(-\) \(P_{2}\) = 0

\(H_{1}\) : \(P_{1}\) \(-\) \(P_{2}\) \(\neq\) 0

prop.test(x= c(107,109),n=c(125,140),alternative = "two.sided",correct = F)
## 
##  2-sample test for equality of proportions without continuity correction

n <- nrow(df_cons)
d <- 0.38577
k <- 3
rho_hat <- (n^2*(1-d/2)+k^2)/(n^2 - k^2)
y_lag <-  lag(df_cons$con, 1)
aaa_lag <-  lag(df_cons$aaa, 1)
dpi_lag <-  lag(df_cons$dpi,1)

y_final <- df_cons$con - rho_hat*y_lag
aaa_final <- df_cons$aaa - rho_hat*aaa_lag
dpi_final <- df_cons$dpi - rho_hat*dpi_lag

y_final[1] <- df_cons$con[1]*sqrt(1-rho_hat^2)
aaa_final[1] <- df_cons$aaa[1]*sqrt(1-rho_hat^2)
dpi_final[1] <- df_cons$dpi[1]*sqrt(1-rho_hat^2)
model_gls <- lm(y_final ~ aaa_final + dpi_final)
